Researchers at the tropical botanical garden in Xishuangbanna, Chinese Academy of Sciences, analyzed Genomic data from 93 COVID-19 samples and found 58 haplotypes based on 120 mutation sites, the haplotypes of patients from the South China Seafood Market were associated with H1, while samples of the older genotypes H3, H13, and H38 were from outside the south China Seafood Market. This confirms the South China Seafood Market is not the source of the virus inference.

The study, published in the Lancet on January 24, followed the first 41 confirmed cases, which were first reported on December 1, a total of 13 cases had no history of contact with the seafood market. In other words, the virus had already infiltrated the lives of Wuhan residents before it entered the seafood market.

The research was conducted by researchers from the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Xishuangbanna, in conjunction with the South China Agricultural University and the Beijing Brain Science Center, and was published Feb. 19 on Chinese Academy of Sciences, a pre release platform for scientific papers.

The authors believe that determining whether the seafood market is the source of the virus is crucial to the search for the source of the virus, as well as to the identification of intermediate hosts, in order to control the outbreak and avoid a recurrence.

####Tracing of whole genome data analysis

This is a population-based genetic analysis, Yu explained to DeepTech. One genotype is not the same as one patient, and a new coronavirus haplotype may be present in many, if not hundreds of people, such as the H1 haplotype, which corresponds to 19 samples, but can be traced back through this, because a haplotype means it could have come from the same source.

The researchers collected genomic data (as of February 12) from 93 samples of COVID-19 shared in the ISAID EpiFluTM database from all over the world, covering 12 countries on four continents. Of these, 39 samples were from infected patients in 11 countries, encoding 31 haplotypes. The 54 samples from China also encoded 31 haplotypes.

Using genome-wide data analysis, they traced the source and spread of the infection and found that the 93 samples received contained 58 haplotypes, of which H13 and H38 were the more "ancient" haplotypes, the haplotype H1 was derived from the haplotype H3.

It should be noted that the haplotypes associated with the south China seafood market were all H1 and its derived haplotypes, while an older haplotype H3 from the Wuhan sample was not associated with the south China Seafood Market. Based on the first patient reports and the time of population expansion, the authors speculate that the COVID-19 in the south China seafood market was imported from elsewhere, where it spread rapidly beyond the market.

The authors also speculate that Haplotypes H13 and H38 are associated with bat coronavirus RaTG13 through an intermediate vector, MV1, which may be an ancestral haplotype, or from an intermediate host or "patient zero. ".

The "ancient" haplotype H13 and H38 samples came from patients in Shenzhen (the first case in Guangdong) and Washington State (the first case in the United States) . Their travel records show that they visited Wuhan from the end of December 2019 to the beginning of January 2020.

Why are there two "old" haplotypes? Yu explained to DeepTech that H13 and H38, as well as H3, had only one nucleotide site difference between them, and it was possible that H3 was the product of a reverse mutation that converted to a different genotype. And both are synonymous mutations, that is, mutations that do not affect gene expression. This means that the two "old" haplotypes are very close together.

H13 and H38 haplotypes were not detected in the existing Wuhan samples, presumably because the existing samples were mainly collected from several designated hospitals and the sampling time was limited to December 24,2019, and January 5,2020. So, if these two haplotypes can be detected in early patients in other hospitals in Wuhan, it will be very helpful to find the source of the virus.

For haplotype H3, the Wuhan sample was found in January 2020, but that doesn't mean the genotype is "younger" . It could be that the virus did not mutate when it was transmitted to the carrier, or that it infected the patient early, but did not become ill, Yu explained.

This is a study based on the sequence of the existing COVID-19 genome, commented an anonymous professor at the Huazhong Agricultural University. Theoretically, depending on the variation, it would be possible to trace the relationship between the samples, whether it's a father-son relationship or a brother-sister relationship, and how many generations it replicates. Then we can finally trace the origin of the earliest new coronavirus. One hypothesis, of course, is that the virus is transmitted from animals to humans.

The discovery of haplotype H3 outside the South China Seafood Market also meant that H3 carriers infected those who went to the market, turning the crowded south China seafood market into a viral flashpoint.

He believes that it is important to trace back to the source, and that this research is being done through big data analysis, which makes a lot of sense. The core of the investigation is the first few people to contract the new coronavirus, and this requires the cooperation of the hospital in particular, but the hospital may not be in the mood or energy to do this right now, and the doctors may not have a background in evolutionary genomics, so they may not realize the value of it.

As for the original carrier, patient zero, he said, it may have been someone who came into contact with bats. In theory, it should be traceable. Even if patient zero is dead, there's still a sample of his blood in one of the hospitals.

Yu said the original haplotype was unlikely to be present in the current patient because the virus mutates too quickly. The earliest date they can get is December 24, because it's hard to trace without an early sample, "We suspect that hospitals in the country may not have preserved tissue from early patients, and we would certainly like to have early samples, " he said.

Yu Wenbin said the study had one shortcoming: of the 93 samples, the Wuhan sample was mainly early, and if more Wuhan samples were sequenced, more evidence might be found in tracing the source, finding haplotypes of H13 and H38, for example, might help identify the source of the virus.

####A piece of good news

The main thrust of the study, Yu said, is to analyze the variation in the entire genome of the new coronavirus, as well as to identify patterns of transmission of the new coronavirus, based on analysis of transmission and spread, and to provide genetic evidence for the origin of the virus.

The researchers found no recombination in the COVID-19 genome, with 120 nucleotides (0.41% of the length) mutated between the 93 genomes and spread evenly across the 10 coding regions. The 120 mutated nucleotides were associated with 119 amino acid codons, of which 79(65.83%) changed the amino acid type and 42(53.17%) changed the physical and chemical properties of the amino acids.

The conclusion that "no reprogramming of the new coronavirus genome has occurred" is good news, meaning that no entirely new strains of the virus will be created.

The study also concluded that the new coronavirus had two significant population expansions prior to Feb. 12.

Based on the timing of the COVID-19, the population expansion that took place before January was December 8, so the virus could have started to spread from person to person in early December or even late November, then it accelerated the interpersonal communication in the south China Seafood Market.

The study puts the time of population expansion before February at Jan. 6, which may be related to the New Year's Day holiday. It should be noted that at this time the National CDC issued a Level 2 emergency response.

The team believes that the early warning had some warning effect, with fewer public events and fewer trips. If the warnings had been heeded more widely, the number of cases spreading nationally and globally would have dropped by mid-to-late January.
